Some religions prescribe the washing of hands for both hygienic and symbolic purposes. The symbolic washing of hands, which consists of using water and not soap to wash their hands, is part of the rituals of washing hands put forward in many religions, including Bahiaism and Hinduism, immersion (tevilah) and ritual removal of hands (Nétilat Yadayim) in Judaism, washing in Christianity and wudhu in Islam. The religions also prescribe washing of hands for hygienic purposes, especially after certain actions.
